":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume De Chamalieres was born about 1150, in Chamalières, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France. He married Marquise D'albon about 1173, in France. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1150–":"umbes 1150–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1135–1170":"1135–1170","1175–1212":"1175–1212","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","about 1173":"umbes 1173","Abt 1150":"umbes 1150","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1155":"1155","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chamalières, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Chamalières, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1150–":"noin 1150–Kuollut","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1135–1170":"1135–1170","1175–1212":"1175–1212","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","about 1